{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493409"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1315"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1315"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.28,0.17,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112864"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1315"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94901"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"698"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43073"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112864"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man with a background of Alzheimer\u2019s disease was admitted for an accidental overdose of diazepam four days ago. He is not prescribed diazepam, and on this single occasion took some of his wife\u0027s supply by mistake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA day prior to his planned discharge, he presents with aggressive behaviour at 12 am in the medical ward. He has been pacing along the corridor and refuses to return to bed. When instructed to go to bed, he starts throwing chairs and pushing security staff members. A low-stimulus environment is set up. Verbal de-escalation and re-orientation is attempted but proves unsuccessful to control his agitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis clinical workup was unremarkable apart from a positive urine drug screen for benzodiazepine on admission.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate to control his agitation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Risperidone","Lorazepam","Flumazenil","Complete Inpatient Treatment Order form","Urgent psychiatry review"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDelirium on the ward is a common clinical presentation faced by junior doctors. In managing delirium, it is important to investigate the underlying cause with physical examination and appropriate laboratory/radiological tests and manage the patient using non-pharmacological measures such as verbal de-escalation and creating a low-stimulus environment as well as treating any physical illness found. However, if non-pharmacological interventions are unsuccessful and the patient continues to be a threat to harming others, short-term medications can be administered. This is to calm the patient down and prevent harm to himself and others. This gives clinicians the opportunity to investigate the underlying cause more effectively and safely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf the options listed, \u003Cstrong\u003Erisperidone\u003C/strong\u003E would be the mainstay pharmacological intervention for acute delirium. It is used as a last resort and may alleviate agitation - though does not treat the underlying cause or reduce duration or severity of delirium. Antipsychotics are also associated with increased mortality if used long-term.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThough not listed as an answer option, haloperidol and olanzapine are also appropriate options for the management of delirium. Haloperidol\u0027s side effect profile and efficacy may be marginally not as good as second generation antipsychotics such as risperidone or olanzapine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBenzodiazepines such as \u003Cstrong\u003Elorazepam\u003C/strong\u003E are less favourable as they often worsen cognition, particularly in those with cognitive impairment. However, lorazepam is the preferred drug in delirium due to alcohol withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlumazenil\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat benzodiazepine overdose and would not be helpful in this situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA psychiatric review\u003C/strong\u003E may be required in this man\u0027s management plan, but is not the next step. Often, psychiatric reviews may not available at night. An \u003Cstrong\u003Ein-patient treatment order \u003C/strong\u003Emay be required if the patient chooses to self-discharge at this stage, but this is not the most immediate management plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Risperidone is the preferred pharmacotherapy for acute delirium."],"references":["Parellada E, Baeza I, de Pablo J, Mart\u00ednez G. Risperidone in the treatment of patients with delirium. J Clin Psychiatry 2004; 65:348.","Campbell N, Boustani MA, Ayub A, et al. Pharmacological management of delirium in hospitalized adults--a systematic evidence review. J Gen Intern Med 2009; 24:848.","Lonergan E, Luxenberg J, Areosa Sastre A, Wyller TB. Benzodiazepines for delirium. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2009; :CD006379."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94901"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1315"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94901"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-07T10:22:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-07T10:22:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1315"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112864"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n